%I A135846 #13 Mar 04 2026 10:50:56
%S A135846 599,691,733,3163,4259,4397,5419,6637,6733,8009,8311,9803,11731,14923,
%T A135846 17291,20627,20873,22777,25111,26339,27947,29339,29389,29527,29917,
%U A135846 34123,34421,34739,34757,36527,36809,38783,40433,40531,41131,42859
%N A135846 Primes p such that the polynomial x^5-x^4-x^3-x^2-x-1 modulo p is completely factorizable.
%C A135846 A135847 and A135843 are complementary subsets of this sequence.
%C A135846 Seems to differ from A106281 only by the initial 599. - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 03 2026
%e A135846 For p=7, the factorization is 6+6x+6x^2+6x^3+6x^4+x^5, and involves an order-5 factor. For p=19, the factorization is (3x+1)(6+4+11x^2+15x^3+x^4) and involves an order-4 factor. For p=599 the factorization is (101+x)(198+x)^2(217+x)(483+x) and all factors are polynomials of order 1 (although one is squared), so 599 is in the list. - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 04 2026
%t A135846 a = {}; Do[poly = PolynomialMod[x^5-x^4-x^3-x^2-x-1, Prime[n]]; c = FactorList[poly, Modulus -> Prime[n]]; If[Sum[c[[m]][[2]], {m, 1, Length[c]}] == 6, AppendTo[a, Prime[n]]], {n, 1, 10000}]; a
%Y A135846 Cf. A135842, A135843, A135844, A135845, A135847.
%K A135846 nonn,changed
%O A135846 1,1
%A A135846 _Artur Jasinski_, Dec 01 2007
